==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''mōþa-'', from Indo-European ''*mē-, *mō-''.

Cognate with Old High German [[muot]] (German [[Mut]]), Old Saxon ''mōd'' (Dutch [[moed]]), Old Norse ''móðr'' ‘anger, grief’ (Swedish [[mod]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐍉𐌸𐍃]] ‘anger, emotion’.  The IE root was also the source of Greek [[μῶθαι]] and Latin [[mos]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /mo:d/

===Noun===
'''mōd''' ''n'' (''pl'' '''mōd''')
# [[heart]], [[mind]], [[feeling]]
# [[courage]], [[pride]], [[grief]], [[anger]]
# a state of mind

